results.notes:
Three of four fruiting bodies growing on the south/west side of Coopers road (at the juncture with the Red Trail near Pakim Pond) under mature pitch pine and oak.
Two fbs were collected, photographed and preserved. One of the fbs had pale vinaceous droplets exuding from the pore surface. The exposed context consistently stained blue — the reaction had a quick onset (~15 sec) and gradually intensified over 1-2 minutes. Unfortunately, I didn’t check the pores for bluing.
KOH stained the pellicle pinkish-magenta; upon absorption of the reagent, the color was deep vinaceous-brown. Ammonia vapors stained the pellicle the same color. I may have performed tests on the flesh, but I didn’t take pix or make notes.
A second collection was made on Oct. 18 and posted as obs 257442.

Livezey in DE, and 3 bases off (all gaps in two sexta-thymine motifs; such gaps are common deletions/insertions events during PRC) from S. hirtellus voucher dfmo0851.001 (accession #KX260618) collected by R. results.notes:
Several basidiomata growing close to each other among mature oaks between Sunset Shelter and Kings Hwy North. At the time they all looked like the same species to me, but now looking at the pix of the two specimens I collected and preserved I am not so sure anymore… Well, I think they are the same thing after all.
Unfortunately, I don’t have pictures showing details of the stipe, so not sure if a partial was there. I don’t see any signs of a PV in the dried material, but it might have just fallen off prior to preservation. At this time, however, this species is presumed to be exannulate.
I felt these were sufficiently interesting to be preserved for RET. A small fragment of the cap was retained for my own herbarium.

DNA Results and Discussion (posted on 25-Dec-20):
> A clean and contiguous nrDNA sequence of 702 bps was obtained from this material by Dr. Kudzma. It consists of the last 46 characters of nrSSU, which is followed by the full-length ITS locus of 570 base pairs and then by the first 86 bps of nrLSU. The ITS1 and ITS2 regions are 198 and 212 bps long, respectively, in this species. The sequence is supported by both reads, with exception of the first 19 characters of ITS1 that are obscured by noise in the forward read but are well-resolved in the reverse read. There is a single ambiguity, “Y” (C/T), in the conserved 5.8S sublocus.
A BLASTn of the ITS sequence revealed what looks like several records of this North American taxon in GenBank:
MF686542: ‘Amanita sp. strain ALW01’ collected in TN; 569/570 = 99.8% similar
MF686539: ‘Amanita sp. strain HMA02 (TENN)’ collected in TN; 568/570 = 99.6% similar
MH211675: ‘Amanita sp. voucher FLAS-F-60629’ collected in FL; 455/457 = 99.6% similar
MH016897: ‘Amanita sp. voucher FLAS-F-60934’ collected in FL; 564/568 = 99.3% similar
KX816058: ‘Uncultured fungus clone ALR11AMP-A1’ collected in MS?; 566/571 = 99.1% similar
The lack of identification attempts at the species level in the GenBank records is not surprising. This species doesn’t really look like any the of common and readily recognized species assignable to sect. Amanita. Also notable is the absence of accessions by RET, though he may have unpublished DNA data (I sent Rod an inquiry).
Next on the hit list are accessions labeled as A. orientigemmata (found in Asia) and A. gioiosa (found in the Mediterranean region), with 98.6-99.1% and 97.1% similarity, respectively. Following these, however, the % identity instantly drops to 93%.
> A distance-based tree was built in GenBank using a wide variety of sect. Amanita accessions of mostly North American material published by RET. It’s shown in Fig. 1. Therein, the NA taxon forms a distinct clade with the aforementioned A. orientigemmata and A. gioiosa. The topology seems to indicate the latter species to be more closely related to our critter. Also, the muscaroid and pantherinoid clades stand out.
> A sequence alignment of A. orientigemmata (2 accessions), A. gioiosa (MH603599), and MO257597 is shown in Fig. 2. The ITS locus is between the magenta-highlighted areas; the light gray areas within the ITS region mark the starting and ending motifs of the conserved 5.8S sublocus.
The are 14 distinct areas where the sequences show their differences. Of these 6 are isolated single nucleotide polymorphisms and 5 others represent gaps due to the variable-length homopolymeric repeats and one case a two-character repeat. The latter group of mismatches are of lesser significance because variation in such motifs often appears intra-specifically in the ITS locus of many fungi. Of the remaining mismatches, the interesting “CAGT” insert in the ITS1 sublocus in gioiosa is noteworthy. Despite all the mismatches, however, the overall sequence structure of the three taxa shows a remarkable similarity, which would be expected in organisms of close kinship. Of course, other loci should be sampled and analyzed for these species to confirm this interesting inference.
Despite the characterization by DNA, the identity of this North American species is still a mystery.

Place: Zadnja Trenta valley, close to 46. switchback of alpine road to Vršič pass, East Julian Alps, Posočje, Slovenia EC.

Comments: Suillus viscidus is not a rare find in Slovenia. It is strictly bound to Larix decidua trees and best recognized by large angular pores and the fact that it is, frankly speaking, an ugly mushroom of indefinite color somewhere among dirty white, gray, beige or pale brown. The whole mushroom is like this. When I first found it I didn’t take pictures of it because I thought it was already decayed and therefore determination impossible. But already young pilei look like this.

There were more than 10 pilei present at the location, mostly solitary, on an area of about 6 by 6 m. All of them grew under the canopies of Larix decidua or close to them. Pilei diameter 3 – 8 cm, surface viscid, cuticle peels very easily; stem 4 – 9 cm tall, 10 – 17 mm in diameter; taste mild, mushroomy; smell indistinctive; SP faint, brownish, oac could not be determined.

results.notes:
To the extent that they are different from one another, this material may represent either Munkia martyris or Munkia chusqueae (≡Shropshiria chusqueae), both of which are said to be characterized by forming conidia inside of cup-shaped sporodochia, as seen in the macro images. Problematically, the dimensions for both those spp. do not exceed 8mm in any direction, which is significantly smaller than the material seen here. Over the past 130 years, various authors have posited a connection between Munkia and a Mycomalus-like teleomorph, but this has yet to be fully substantiated. Contradictions in the literature regarding conidial morphology and other characters further complicate the study of these often beautiful and widely underappreciated fungi.

Unfortunately, our sections turned up nothing particularly worth photographing, partly on account of the hardness of the tissue (Stevens says it should be “boil[ed] in dilute potash,” which was neither readily on hand in the FLOR herbarium, nor would we have had time to cook the specimen if it were possible to). What’s more, we could locate no conidia; not in any sporodochial cavity we examined, not floating around the medium, not a one. Better luck next time.

We are grateful to MicoLab, particularly Maria Alice Neves and Caue Oliveira, for graciously accommodating our curiosity in these and other Clavicipitaceous specimens.

results.notes: un fungi común (junto a las xylarias) en el Humedal La Conejera. Daldinia cf. concentrica, sus estromas son semiglobosos llegando a 7-10 cm de diámetro. El cuerpo va oscureciendo según su maduración, internamente presenta zonas concéntricas de color gris-morron. La esporada es de color oscuro y su espora de forma elíptica. Por sus caracteres macro y micro da para D. concentrica, sin embargo no se ha logrado observar con claridad la hendidura sigmoide en la espora, caracter de la especie.
